  "description": "¶Entry conditions Use axiomatic arithmetic only when you need a formal foundation for numbers and their operations, not just an informal counting story.\n¶Definitions The Peano axioms describe the natural numbers (N,0,S)(\\mathbb{N},0,S):\n00 is a natural number. If nn is a natural number, then S(n)S(n) is a natural number. 00 is not the successor of any natural number. If S(n)=S(m)S(n)=S(m), then n=mn=m. Induction: if a set contains 00 and is closed under successor, it contains all natural numbers. ¶Vocabulary (plain language) Axiom: a rule accepted as a starting point. Successor: the operation that produces the next number. Induction: a proof rule for all natural numbers. ¶Symbols used N\\mathbb{N}: the natural numbers. S(n)S(n): the successor of nn. ¶Intuition Rather than saying \u0026ldquo;numbers are what you count,\u0026rdquo; the axioms say: start with 00 and repeatedly apply successor. This gives a structure where \u0026ldquo;counting\u0026rdquo; can be defined and proved.\n",
